 The brokers intermediate the trade for customers, and demand collateral fr=
om the customers, and if the customers are a little short on collateral the=
n the broker has to weigh its risk of=C2=A0not=C2=A0liquidating the positio=
n (it might go down more, and then the broker loses money) versus its risk =
of liquidating the position (that might=C2=A0cause=C2=A0it to go down more,=
 plus the customer will be mad).Last week FT Alphaville reported on somethi=
ng that=C2=A0Chris Edmonds of ICE said at the CFTC roundtable:On ... the id=
ea of =E2=80=98defaulters pay=E2=80=99. I get that. Love that, right.=C2=A0=
And that works really well for guys who are in big shops, because they neve=
r default. They want to tell you they never default. And we=E2=80=99re just=
