adding=3D"0">
<tr>
<td class=3D"body-header-container" style=3D"border-collapse: collapse; mso=
-table-lspace: 0pt; mso-table-rspace: 0pt;">
<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Clearing</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The basic philosophical=C2=A0differenc=
e between the traditional financial system and the cryptocurrency system is=
 that traditional finance is=C2=A0<em>about the extension of credit</em>, a=
nd crypto is=C2=A0<em>not</em>. That is an exaggeration in various ways, bu=
t I think that it is essentially true.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">So c=
onsider the simplest aspects of these systems. Like money: A US dollar=C2=
=A0<em>is</em>, essentially, <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness=
.com/click/27911512.270612/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2Fy=
dGljbGVzLzIwMjItMDUtMzEvcnVzc2lhLWhhcy1zb21lLWRvbGxhcnMtc29tZXdoZXJlP2NtcGl=
kPUJCRDA2MDEyMl9NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbG=
V0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIyMDYwMSZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b85=
24a319a23cB9245d28f" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=
=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; bord=
er-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: so=
lid; background-color: #ccc;"> an entry on the ledger of a bank</a>, repres=
enting that bank=E2=80=99s debt to you. Basically every dollar that you own=
 is <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/27911512.27061=
2/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMTgtMDUtMTcvc=
HV0LXlvdXItYml0Y29pbnMtaW4tdGhlLW1vbmV5LW1hcmtldD9jbXBpZD1CQkQwNjAxMjJfTU9O=
RVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0=
yMjA2MDEmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBd38853d6"=
 itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"=
color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px;=
 border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color=
: #ccc;"> someone else=E2=80=99s debt to you</a>. A Bitcoin is not. A Bitco=
in is an entry on the decentralized ledger of Bitcoin; there is a fixed sup=
ply of Bitcoins; owning a Bitcoin is like owning a gold nugget; no debt is =
involved.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Or take trading.=C2=A0Every=
 time you trade a stock, in the US, <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergb=
usiness.com/click/27911512.270612/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGlua=
W9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMDEtMjkvcmVkZGl0LXRyYWRlcnMtb24tcm9iaW5ob29kLWFyZS1v=
bi1ib3RoLXNpZGVzLW9mLWdhbWVzdG9wP2NtcGlkPUJCRDA2MDEyMl9NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9=
tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIyMDYwMSZ1dG1fY2=
FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB63ea679a" itemprop=3D"Sto=
ryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; =
text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-c=
olor: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> there =
is an extension of credit</a>. You and I agree on a trade on Wednesday, and=
 we actually settle =E2=80=94=C2=A0I give you the money and you hand over t=
he stock =E2=80=94=C2=A0on Friday. In the meantime, there is credit risk: I=
f I disappear you don=E2=80=99t get your money; if you disappear I don=E2=
=80=99t get my stock. The traditional financial system deals with this risk=
 through layers of intermediation, trust and collateral requirements: My br=
oker makes sure I=E2=80=99m good for the money, a clearinghouse demands col=
lateral from my broker to make sure it=E2=80=99s good for the money, etc. (=
And <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/27911512.27061=
2/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9uZXdzL3ByZXNzLXJlbGVhc2UvMjAyMi0yMQ/607f07ceef=
4b8524a319a23cB279c7ae6" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" tar=
get=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; b=
order-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style:=
 solid; background-color: #ccc;">there is a plan</a> to change this =E2=80=
=9CT+2=E2=80=9D settlement to =E2=80=9CT+1,=E2=80=9D so we exchange the cas=
h for stock on Thursday instead of Friday, reducing the credit risk.) Meanw=
hile in the crypto system the paradigmatic=C2=A0trades occur=C2=A0on the bl=
ockchain: You and I agree on a trade on some decentralized exchange, and I =
send you my stablecoins and you send me your crypto at the same time the tr=
ansaction is agreed; the trade and settlement are simultaneous.</p><p style=
=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Many advocates of crypto <em>like</em> this; they thin=
k that crypto=E2=80=99s philosophical uneasiness with=C2=A0credit is good. =
Money without debt =E2=80=94=C2=A0without fractional-reserve banking =E2=80=
=94=C2=A0is sounder, less inflationary and safer, they argue; trading with =
instant settlement is clearer and more logical and safer than trading with =
delayed settlement and credit risk.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But whe=
ther you like it or not this difference is=C2=A0deeply baked into the mecha=
nics of crypto. In some sense the entities of traditional finance are <em>p=
eople</em> and <em>companies</em>, and their counterparties can make credit=
 decisions based on thick sets of information about them. Your bank can loo=
k at your credit report and payment history before giving you a credit card=
; an investment bank can consider a hedge fund=E2=80=99s track record and p=
rospects of future business and risk-management protocols =E2=80=94=C2=A0an=
d how much the bank=E2=80=99s salesperson=C2=A0<em>likes</em> the hedge fun=
d=E2=80=99s manager =E2=80=94=C2=A0before extending it a margin loan. Also =
if you default on your credit card the bank can sue you and make the whole =
rest of your life difficult; if the hedge fund defaults on a margin loan th=
e bank can blackball its manager from future business. In crypto the entiti=
es are=C2=A0<em>blockchain addresses</em>, and they are thinner.[1] You set=
 up a wallet, you have a private key, the wallet interacts with other walle=
ts, you don=E2=80=99t know the names of the people who own those wallets, t=
hey don=E2=80=99t know your name, and only=C2=A0<em>what happens on the blo=
ckchain=C2=A0</em>is relevant to any of your or their decisions. The bank k=
nows where you live; the blockchain does not.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0=
;">Still, credit is kind of an important part of a financial system? People=
 want to borrow money to do stuff. Sometimes this is normal business or per=
sonal stuff: People want to borrow money to start a business or build a fac=
tory or buy a house or whatever. If crypto is going to displace or compete =
with the traditional financial system, it will need to find ways to do that=
 sort of lending. This seems to me like a hard and rather unsolved problem =
in crypto, and I don=E2=80=99t think a lot of people are taking out mortgag=
es from the blockchain.[2]</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But credit is al=
so a very useful aspect of many forms of=C2=A0<em>trading</em>. People like=
 to do=C2=A0<em>trades=C2=A0</em>that involve credit. Some people like to b=
uy financial instruments (stock, cryptocurrencies, etc.) on margin: They pu=
t up some money of their own, borrow some money from their broker, and buy =
more stock than they can currently pay for. Or they like to do derivatives =
trades (swaps, futures) that have that basic profile: You put up a little b=
it of money to get exposure to a larger amount of some financial instrument=
. Or they like to trade options, which involve an extension of credit: If I=
 sell you a call option on some stock, then I owe you the stock (in some ci=
rcumstances), and you have to trust that I will actually be able to deliver=
 it.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The crypto system=C2=A0<em>is</em>=C2=
=A0able to extend=C2=A0<em>that=C2=A0</em>sort of credit. That=E2=80=99s re=
latively easy. Margin loans and futures and options are all forms of levera=
ge that are (1) secured (2) by traded collateral and (3) subject to margin =
calls. If you buy $200 worth of stock with $100 of your own money and $100 =
of margin loans from a broker, the broker will feel fairly safe: It has $20=
0 worth of stock to cover its $100 loan. If the stock goes down to $140, th=
e broker will feel less safe, and will demand that you put up some more of =
your own money. If you don=E2=80=99t do that quickly, the broker will sell =
the stock =E2=80=94=C2=A0perhaps for $120 =E2=80=94=C2=A0and pay itself bac=
k, no problem. (If the stock goes down to $80 quickly, that=C2=A0<em>is=C2=
=A0</em>a problem, but these are understandable problems and the broker wil=
l set the margin levels so that it is comfortable with the risk.)</p><p sty=
le=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And because crypto trades 24 hours a day, seven days=
 a week,=C2=A0and is very tech-forward, crypto is pretty good at <em>this</=
em> sort of thing. All sorts of crypto trading platforms offer leverage lik=
e this: You can put up a little bit of money to buy a lot of exposure to so=
me cryptocurrency, and the platform monitors the value of the=C2=A0cryptocu=
rrency, and if it goes down the platform sells the cryptocurrency=C2=A0you =
own to repay its loan. And this can all be done automatically, 24/7. It is =
tricky because lots of crypto stuff is very=C2=A0<em>volatile</em>, and the=
re is limited trading history, but it is all sort of in the category of=C2=
=A0solvable math problems. No thick sorts of credit extension are required:=
 The trading platform doesn=E2=80=99t have to know where you live or have a=
 good personal rapport with you; everything can be automated and done =E2=
=80=9Con-chain,=E2=80=9D based solely on the blockchain=E2=80=99s knowledge=
 of your crypto wallet.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In the traditional =
financial system, very few things work=C2=A0like this. One thing that mostl=
y does is a margin account at a retail stock brokerage: If your stock decli=
nes, you will get a margin call, and if you don=E2=80=99t post margin withi=
n a defined and fairly tight time frame your broker will sell the stock, an=
d this really might all be done by a computer in a pretty formulaic way. Bu=
t if you have a big enough account =E2=80=94=C2=A0if you are a big hedge fu=
nd or family office =E2=80=94=C2=A0it doesn=E2=80=99t work that way. When C=
redit Suisse Group AG decided that Archegos Capital Management did not have=
 enough collateral in its margin account, a Credit Suisse representative ca=
lled Archegos and asked it to post more collateral, and Archegos said, <a h=
ref=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/27911512.270612/aHR0cH=
M6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMDctMjkvYXJjaGVnb=
3Mtd2FzLXRvby1idXN5LWZvci1tYXJnaW4tY2FsbHM_Y21waWQ9QkJEMDYwMTIyX01PTkVZU1RV=
RkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjIwNjA=
xJnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB6d35d6a9" itempr=
op=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: =
#000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border=
-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;=
"> sorry, we are really busy this week, let=E2=80=99s discuss next week</a>=
. In theory Credit Suisse could have liquidated Archegos=E2=80=99s position=
s, but in practice that would have been <em>rude</em>, so it didn=E2=80=99t=
. Credit Suisse did not extend credit to Archegos based on some defined for=
mulaic function of the value of its collateral; Credit Suisse extended cred=
it to Archegos based on some fuzzy holistic relationship-based function of =
how much business it hoped to do with Archegos, how much the Credit Suisse =
people liked the Archegos people, how its traders <em>felt</em> about the c=
ollateral, when its risk committees had meetings, stuff like that.</p><p st=
yle=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And away from margin lending for trading, almost no=
thing works like this. You don=E2=80=99t get a margin call on your mortgage=
 if the value of your house goes down; your bank is only dimly aware=C2=A0i=
f the value of your house goes=C2=A0down, since it doesn=E2=80=99t trade on=
 an exchange. Some companies take out corporate loans that have to be paid =
back if their earnings go down too much =E2=80=94=C2=A0though this is <a hr=
ef=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/27911512.270612/aHR0cHM=
6Ly93d3cucGF1bHdlaXNzLmNvbS9tZWRpYS8zOTc4ODg3L2dvb2Rpc29uX3dhZ25lcl9wcmFjdG=
ljYWxsYXdfYXVnMjAxOV91cGRhdGUucGRm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB29889dae" itemp=
