 #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> Bloomberg l=
ast week</a>:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Wall Street excha=
nges and other firms zeroed in on their objection to a proposal US regulato=
rs are considering that would allow retail investors to trade crypto deriva=
tives directly on a popular digital asset platform.</p><p style=3D"margin: =
16px 0;">The plan -- from crypto firm FTX -- would take banks and other fin=
ancial intermediaries out of Bitcoin and Ether futures trades that use marg=
in. At a roundtable on Wednesday hosted by the Commodity Futures Trading Co=
mmission, which is reviewing the proposal, executives from firms including =
CME Group Inc. and Intercontinental Exchange Inc. said the change could add=
 risks to the market. ...</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">FTX=E2=80=99s CEO=
 Sam Bankman-Fried, who swapped his infamous t-shirt and shorts for a suit,=
 defended his proposal, saying it reduces risk because the firm=E2=80=99s m=
odel would use algorithms to monitor trades seven days a week. The crypto b=
illionaire has said his approach would increase competition and opportuniti=
es for mom-and-pop investors.=C2=A0</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16p=
x 0;">In the typical US market structure, an=C2=A0exchange (where trades ar=
e agreed) is associated with a clearinghouse (where the credit is extended)=
, and the clearinghouse=C2=A0has members, who are large trading firms (bank=
s, brokers, etc.). The members intermediate trades for their customers, who=
 are individuals or smaller trading firms. The members post collateral with=
 the clearinghouse to secure their customers=E2=80=99 trades, and the membe=
rs extend credit to the customers (who in turn generally post collateral wi=
th the members). If a member has posted insufficient collateral, the cleari=
nghouse will call it up and say =E2=80=9Cpost more collateral,=E2=80=9D and=
 the member will either (1) post more collateral and everything is fine, or=
 (2) default=C2=A0and everything is bad, or (3) say =E2=80=9CI don=E2=80=99=
t have more money right now but let=E2=80=99s work something out.=E2=80=9D =
And then all the thick offline human factors come into play.=C2=A0</p><p st=
yle=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And that process repeats at the customer level: The=
 brokers intermediate the trade for customers, and demand collateral from t=
he customers, and if the customers are a little short on collateral then th=
e broker has to weigh its risk of=C2=A0<em>not=C2=A0</em>liquidating the po=
sition (it might go down more, and then the broker loses money) versus its =
risk of liquidating the position (that might=C2=A0<em>cause=C2=A0</em>it to=
 go down more, plus the customer will be mad).</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px =
0;">Last week <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/2791=
1512.270612/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuZnQuY29tL2NvbnRlbnQvMjE2ODY2ZTctY2VjYi00NjUwLWF=
lYTUtYjlkZWRjN2Q3Yzdj/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBea3a10ae" itemprop=3D"StoryL=
ink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; tex=
t-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-colo=
r: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">FT Alphavi=
lle reported</a> on something that=C2=A0Chris Edmonds of ICE said at the CF=
TC roundtable:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">On ... the idea =
of =E2=80=98defaulters pay=E2=80=99. I get that. Love that, right.=C2=A0And=
 that works really well for guys who are in big shops, because they never d=
efault. They want to tell you they never default. And we=E2=80=99re just go=
ing to call that out at the moment. At the beginning of the pandemic =E2=80=
=94 I=E2=80=99m not going to name the person, but they=E2=80=99re in the ro=
om - there was a technical issue. Point: he doesn=E2=80=99t have to worry a=
bout that in the proposed model, right, that=E2=80=99s not there. But it wo=
uld=E2=80=99ve been cataclysmic at that moment in time. We knew the issue, =
to Gerry=E2=80=99s point about know-the-customer. We knew where it was. And=
 we chose to give the appropriate amount of time not to dislocate the marke=
t and create a bigger stress on that.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">So fo=
r us at the end of the day, it=E2=80=99s our job to do no harm. It=E2=80=99=
s our job to hold everyone. It=E2=80=99s the question of when you=E2=80=99r=
e calling the default. There are lots of examples in history that many of u=
s around this table have lived around and now=E2=80=99d say, you know, =E2=
=80=9CI think they=E2=80=99re in default.=E2=80=9D Gerry may say =E2=80=9Cn=
ope they=E2=80=99re not in default,=E2=80=9D at that point. And that consen=
sus when that default takes place, we react pretty well.</p><p style=3D"mar=
gin: 16px 0;">But I had the keys to the castle at that point in time, and i=
t would=E2=80=99ve been a very bad day. And that person sits in this room, =
and they know exactly who I=E2=80=99m talking about.</p></blockquote><p sty=
le=3D"margin: 16px 0;">That is: =E2=80=9CGuys who are in big shops=E2=80=9D=
 never default, because if they get a margin call from their clearinghouse =
and they happen not to have the money available, they say =E2=80=9Ccall us =
tomorrow,=E2=80=9D and the clearinghouse says =E2=80=9Cah yes right.=E2=80=
=9D Because they are friends, because the clearinghouse knows (or thinks) f=
rom context clues that they=E2=80=99re good for it, or because the clearing=
house concludes that it would be =E2=80=9Ca very bad day=E2=80=9D if it liq=
uidates=C2=A0a big firm and so takes the risk that it will have the money t=
omorrow.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Meanwhile the FTX proposal =E2=80=
=94=C2=A0here is <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/2=
7911512.270612/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuZnR4cG9saWN5LmNvbS9wb3N0cy9mdHgtY2xlYXJpbmdo=
b3VzZS1hcHBsaWNhdGlvbi1iZWZvcmUtY2Z0Yw/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB53c2f08b" i=
temprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"co=
lor: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; b=
order-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: =
#ccc;">FTX=E2=80=99s overview</a>, and the CFTC=E2=80=99s <a href=3D"https:=
//link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/27911512.270612/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuY2Z=
0Yy5nb3YvUHJlc3NSb29tL1ByZXNzUmVsZWFzZXMvODQ5OS0yMg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23=
cB60224f9c" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank=
" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-=
width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; backg=
round-color: #ccc;">request for comment</a> =E2=80=94 is that it will run i=
ts exchange, and it will run the clearinghouse, and customers will trade wi=
th it directly, and FTX will set their margin requirements and hold on to t=
he margin for them, and if they fall below the margin requirements=C2=A0the=
 algorithm will liquidate their positions. Everyone is treated equally and =
algorithmically; the risk management is mechanical and statistical rather t=
han a guy saying =E2=80=9CI had the keys to the castle at that point in tim=
e.=E2=80=9D From the <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/cli=
ck/27911512.270612/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuY2Z0Yy5nb3YvbWVkaWEvNzAzMS9Db21tZW50RlRY=
QW1lbmRlZE9yZGVyL2Rvd25sb2Fk/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB9e97ba11" itemprop=3D=
"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #0000=
00; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bott=
om-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">req=
uest for comment</a>:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">FTX=E2=80=
=99s model does not contemplate receiving any funds from a participant not =
on deposit when the trade is executed. FTX has two margin requirements for =
its participants, the initial margin requirement and the maintenance margin=
 requirement. The initial margin requirement is the amount of margin the pa=
rticipant must post to open a position. Maintenance margin is a set minimum=
 percentage of the notional value of the portfolio that the margin on depos=
it must exceed. A participant=E2=80=99s margin level is recalculated every =
30 seconds as positions are marked to market, and if the collateral on depo=
sit falls below the maintenance margin level, FTX=E2=80=99s automated syste=
m will begin to liquidate the portfolio. The automated system will liquidat=
e 10 percent of a portfolio at a time by placing offsetting orders on the c=
entral limit order book. Once the liquidation process results in collateral=
 on deposit that exceeds the maintenance margin requirement, the liquidatio=
n will stop. Because the liquidation is done automatically and positions ar=
e marked to market every 30 seconds, these liquidations can occur at any ti=
me, on a =E2=80=9C24-7=E2=80=9D basis.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: =
16px 0;">The point is not that this is=C2=A0<em>risk-free</em>; it isn=E2=
=80=99t, and there are various backstops =E2=80=94=C2=A0people who will bea=
r the losses =E2=80=94=C2=A0in case the portfolio falls faster than FTX can=
 liquidate it.[3] The point is just that the risk is managed formulaically =
and, as it were, =E2=80=9Con-chain.=E2=80=9D FTX=E2=80=99s margining model =
does not ask questions like =E2=80=9Chow big is this customer=E2=80=99s bal=
ance sheet=E2=80=9D or =E2=80=9Chow good is this customer=E2=80=99s reputat=
ion=E2=80=9D or=C2=A0=E2=80=9Chow much business can we expect to do with th=
is customer in the future.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0The=C2=A0<em>customer=C2=A0</em>is=
 irrelevant to the credit decision; only the <em>account=C2=A0</em>matters:=
=C2=A0=E2=80=9CFTX=E2=80=99s model does not contemplate receiving any funds=
 from a participant not on deposit when the trade is executed.=E2=80=9D FTX=
 doesn=E2=80=99t care if the customer is good for the money; it only cares =
about the value of the collateral and the volatility of the asset.=C2=A0</p=
><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">There are=C2=A0debates about whether this is =
good or bad; simplistically, you=E2=80=99d expect the FTX model to lead to=
=C2=A0<em>more=C2=A0</em>defaults and liquidations, but for those defaults =
to be=C2=A0<em>less bad</em>. In the traditional system, sometimes people w=
ill have a =E2=80=9Ctechnical issue,=E2=80=9D and the exchange will =E2=80=
=9Cgive the appropriate amount of time not to dislocate the market and crea=
te a bigger stress on that,=E2=80=9D and it will work out fine =E2=80=94=C2=
=A0but occasionally it=C2=A0<em>won=E2=80=99t=C2=A0</em>work out fine, and =
by delaying the exchange will have caused a much bigger problem.</p><p styl=
e=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Mostly though I just want to point out that these are=
 different philosophies. The FTX-type approach is more or less necessary fo=
r decentralized finance: If you want financial systems to be accessible by =
anyone in a permissionless, decentralized way, you need the extension of cr=
edit to be formulaic and asset-based and =E2=80=9Con-chain.=E2=80=9D If you=
 want the crypto financial system to take over the regular financial system=
, one crucial step is to get the CFTC to approve this sort of trading.</p><=
p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">On the other hand the traditional, relationship=
-based approach has its points too. Here=E2=80=99s <a href=3D"https://link.=
mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/27911512.270612/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuZnQuY29tL2=
NvbnRlbnQvMjk1YTY2YmMtMGY5OS00MjE1LWE2YjAtZGEwYjhhMmNjZDcw/607f07ceef4b8524=
a319a23cB5fe9dec6" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D=
"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-=
bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid=
; background-color: #ccc;">Gary Silverman at the Financial Times</a>:</p><b=
lockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Some of the nation=E2=80=99s farmers=
 are worried that billionaire chief executive of the FTX cryptocurrency exc=
hange could cost them sleep. =E2=80=A6</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Nels=
on Neale, president of CHS Hedging, the futures brokerage arm of a leading =
US farmer co-operative, said at the CFTC meeting that an overnight automate=
d liquidation posed a bigger threat to farmers who turn to the futures mark=
ets to hedge their risks than to traders who use such contracts for =E2=80=
=9Cspeculation=E2=80=9D.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CWith an a=
uto-liquidation scheme, a crypto trader goes to bed at 11pm and wakes up at=
 7am and, all of a sudden, he=E2=80=99s been knocked out of his position, o=
r liquidated =E2=80=94 a bad day certainly, but perhaps not as bad if we co=
nsider the same scenario for the American farmer,=E2=80=9D he said.</p><p s=
tyle=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CHe goes to bed with a corn position to he=
dge his physical inventory at 11pm, wakes up at 7am, or probably a bit earl=
ier, and he has no position. All of a sudden, the value of his inventory go=
es down considerably=E2=80=89.=E2=80=89.=E2=80=89.=E2=80=89He may have loan=
 obligations he may no longer be able to commit to.=E2=80=9D</p></blockquot=
e><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In the traditional system, if the price of c=
orn drops at midnight, and your broker calls you up for more margin, and yo=
u don=E2=80=99t post more margin, your broker thinks =E2=80=9Caha you are a=
sleep=E2=80=9D and waits until the morning to call you again. But =E2=80=9C=
humans are asleep at midnight=E2=80=9D is the sort of off-chain information=
 that a purely algorithmic approach would ignore.</p><table class=3D"livein=
